00:31:06,464 --> 00:31:08,091
You really think so?

549
00:31:08,166 --> 00:31:10,157
Absolutely. You've been
terrific for him, John.

550
00:31:10,235 --> 00:31:11,702
He's been good for me, too.

551
00:31:11,769 --> 00:31:13,293
It's been kind of fun.

552
00:31:13,438 --> 00:31:15,804
I have a lead on somebody
to take over at the house.

553
00:31:15,874 --> 00:31:17,273
It should only be
a day or two.

554
00:31:17,342 --> 00:31:19,401
That's okay. I didn't know
what you were doing,

555
00:31:19,477 --> 00:31:20,739
so I changed my schedule.

556
00:31:20,812 --> 00:31:22,177
I can stay
until Mom gets home.

557
00:31:22,247 --> 00:31:23,305
Really?

558
00:31:23,381 --> 00:31:24,541
Yeah, no big deal.

559
00:31:38,730 --> 00:31:40,095
Hi, Bette.

560
00:31:54,212 --> 00:31:55,270
Are you all right?

561
00:31:55,346 --> 00:31:56,335
Yeah.

562
00:31:56,414 --> 00:31:58,006
You taking your
blood-pressure pills?

563
00:31:58,082 --> 00:31:59,242
Are you eating?

564
00:31:59,317 --> 00:32:00,944
Yeah, I'm fine, Bette.

565
00:32:01,085 --> 00:32:02,712
I make my own bed now.

566
00:32:03,054 --> 00:32:04,817
And I do the dishes.

567
00:32:05,089 --> 00:32:06,750
John is teaching me to cook.

568
00:32:06,891 --> 00:32:08,552
He's like a regular wife.

569
00:32:09,160 --> 00:32:11,321
Just keep him alive
till I get home.

570
00:32:11,396 --> 00:32:13,694
Thank you for
your confidence.

571
00:32:15,733 --> 00:32:17,200
Mom looks good, doesn't she?

572
00:32:17,268 --> 00:32:18,860
Yeah, wonderful.

573
00:32:19,003 --> 00:32:20,595
I never go anywhere
without my tubes.

574
00:32:20,672 --> 00:32:21,900
I meant your color, Mom.

575
00:32:22,040 --> 00:32:23,268
My color?

576
00:32:23,574 --> 00:32:25,633
What are you, a decorator?

577
00:32:25,910 --> 00:32:27,605
And don't call me Mom.

578
00:32:27,745 --> 00:32:29,440
I don't call you Son, do I?

579
00:32:30,815 --> 00:32:32,806
Stop trying to be
so nice to my mother, Mario.

580
00:32:32,884 --> 00:32:34,351
You're gonna kill her.

581
00:32:34,419 --> 00:32:35,909
Why are you cooking?

582
00:32:35,987 --> 00:32:37,921
There's food
prepared in the freezer.

583
00:32:37,989 --> 00:32:39,115
I told you.

584
00:32:39,190 --> 00:32:41,249
It's just for
a little variety, that's all.

585
00:32:41,326 --> 00:32:42,691
Last night we had salmon.

586
00:32:42,760 --> 00:32:44,421
The night before
that we had coq au vin.

587
00:32:44,495 --> 00:32:46,156
Your father
doesn't like foreign food.

588
00:32:46,230 --> 00:32:48,460
It's not foreign. It's
just chicken in red wine.

589
00:32:48,533 --> 00:32:50,501
He's not allowed
to have red wine.

590
00:32:50,568 --> 00:32:52,263
Mom, it was this much.

591
00:32:52,337 --> 00:32:55,101
I don't want him becoming an
alcoholic while I'm in here.

592
00:32:55,173 --> 00:32:56,902
Nobody ever
became an alcoholic

593
00:32:56,975 --> 00:32:58,602
from coq au vin.

594
00:32:58,676 --> 00:33:02,407
Take it easy, Bette.
Don't get all excited.

595
00:33:03,114 --> 00:33:05,412
You just concentrate
on getting better

596
00:33:05,550 --> 00:33:07,848
and don't worry about me.
You hear?

597
00:33:17,662 --> 00:33:19,254
You sure you
wanna come up, Dad?

598
00:33:19,330 --> 00:33:20,797
It could be a long meeting.

599
00:33:20,865 --> 00:33:24,357
No, I'll come up.
I'll be okay.

600
00:33:25,436 --> 00:33:28,337
I could buy you a lunch here,
you could catch a movie.

601
00:33:28,439 --> 00:33:29,667
I'll sit,
I'll read a magazine.

602
00:33:29,741 --> 00:33:31,868
I'll be fine.

603
00:33:31,943 --> 00:33:33,706
All right.

604
00:33:41,819 --> 00:33:43,514
John Tremont to see
Vic Walton, please.

605
00:33:43,588 --> 00:33:44,953
He's expecting you.

606
00:33:45,023 --> 00:33:47,014
Dad, you sure you're
gonna be okay out here

607
00:33:47,191 --> 00:33:48,488
with all this construction?

608
00:33:48,559 --> 00:33:51,528
Sure, as long as no one throws
a drop cloth over me.

609
00:33:51,696 --> 00:33:53,596
John, good to see you.

610
00:33:54,065 --> 00:33:55,430
Pardon our mess.

611
00:33:55,500 --> 00:33:57,161
No problem.
Good to see you, too, Vic.

612
00:33:57,235 --> 00:33:58,896
This is my father,
Jake Tremont.

613
00:33:59,037 --> 00:34:00,061
Dad, this is Vic Walton.

614
00:34:00,138 --> 00:34:01,332
Nice to meet you,
Mr. Tremont.

615
00:34:01,406 --> 00:34:02,395
And you.

616
00:34:02,473 --> 00:34:03,872
We're gonna be
here about an hour?

617
00:34:03,941 --> 00:34:04,965
I'd say.

618
00:34:05,043 --> 00:34:07,238
All right, well, make yourself
comfortable here, Dad.

619
00:34:07,311 --> 00:34:08,300
Wait a minute.

620
00:34:08,379 --> 00:34:10,313
We don't have to leave
your father out here.

621
00:34:10,381 --> 00:34:12,372
Mr. Tremont, why don't you
come in and sit with us?

622
00:34:12,450 --> 00:34:13,849
I don't think that-

623
00:34:13,918 --> 00:34:15,442
Don't be silly. Come on in.

624
00:34:17,688 --> 00:34:20,589
Ralph, we've given you
every benefit of the doubt

625
00:34:20,691 --> 00:34:22,352
and yet our projections

626
00:34:22,493 --> 00:34:25,121
still come up 20%
less than yours.

627
00:34:26,030 --> 00:34:27,327
How can you be so confident?

628
00:34:27,398 --> 00:34:30,265
You've-you've never run
a business like this before.

629
00:34:30,334 --> 00:34:31,858
And if you're wrong,

630
00:34:31,936 --> 00:34:33,733
we'll be the
laughingstock of the industry

631
00:34:33,871 --> 00:34:35,668
and you'll be off
on another deal.

632
00:34:35,740 --> 00:34:37,469
Forget about
running the cannery.

633
00:34:37,542 --> 00:34:39,635
It loses money
every day it's open

634
00:34:39,710 --> 00:34:40,938
but the property it's on

635
00:34:41,012 --> 00:34:42,502
is worth
at least $50 million.

636
00:34:42,580 --> 00:34:44,445
How can you be sure
of the $50 million?

637
00:34:44,515 --> 00:34:46,745
We think it's a stretch
to bring it to $40 million.

638
00:34:46,818 --> 00:34:48,513
I'd like to see
some supporting data.

639
00:34:48,586 --> 00:34:50,144
If it's supporting data
you need,

640
00:34:50,221 --> 00:34:53,349
Brian will give you a package
at the end of the meeting.

641
00:34:53,491 --> 00:34:55,516
Now can I get
back to my case?

642
00:34:55,593 --> 00:34:56,992
The real estate
is $50 million

643
00:34:57,061 --> 00:34:58,585
and we should have no problem

644
00:34:58,696 --> 00:35:00,493
turning around their
trucking operation.

645
00:35:00,565 --> 00:35:02,328
They let the overhead
get out of hand

646
00:35:02,400 --> 00:35:04,300
but we have
a schedule that shows us

647
00:35:04,368 --> 00:35:06,302
cutting back 10% of
the administrative staff

648
00:35:06,370 --> 00:35:07,530
in a few months.

649
00:35:07,605 --> 00:35:09,197
Aren't you better
off just selling it?

650
00:35:09,273 --> 00:35:10,535
And getting it off your books?

651
00:35:10,608 --> 00:35:12,439
There's no need to,
if we can make it work.

652
00:35:12,510 --> 00:35:14,068
I don't think they
ever focused on it.

653
00:35:14,145 --> 00:35:15,544
I think we can turn it.

654
00:35:15,847 --> 00:35:18,179
The last piece is
food wholesaling,

655
00:35:18,249 --> 00:35:20,410
which has been
a good sector thus far.

656
00:35:20,485 --> 00:35:22,885
Now our
cash flow projections

657
00:35:22,954 --> 00:35:24,922
for the division
may look aggressive

658
00:35:24,989 --> 00:35:27,014
but we're comfortable
with them.

659
00:35:27,091 --> 00:35:28,558
So, all in all,

660
00:35:28,793 --> 00:35:31,421
the banks shouldn't have
any problem financing us.

661
00:35:35,700 --> 00:35:37,167
Well, that was fun.

662
00:35:37,235 --> 00:35:40,102
Johnny, what the hell was
goin' on back there?

663
00:35:40,171 --> 00:35:41,832
Well, we were talking
about buying

664
00:35:41,906 --> 00:35:43,305
a salmon cannery, Dad.

665
00:35:43,374 --> 00:35:46,275
I didn't know you knew
about stuff like that.

666
00:35:46,344 --> 00:35:48,107
Actually, I don't.

667
00:35:48,179 --> 00:35:50,704
The guy coming to us
for money doesn't either.

668
00:35:50,781 --> 00:35:52,214
We're just gonna
buy the company

669
00:35:52,283 --> 00:35:53,773
and then close it down.

670
00:35:55,520 --> 00:35:57,249
That's your job?

671
00:35:57,321 --> 00:35:59,346
You buy companies,
then close them down?

672
00:35:59,423 --> 00:36:02,483
It's a little more
complicated than that, Dad.

673
00:36:02,693 --> 00:36:04,661
Take this cannery,
for instance.

674
00:36:04,795 --> 00:36:06,763
Turns out to be
a lousy business.

675
00:36:06,831 --> 00:36:08,526
It's
third-generation management,

676
00:36:08,599 --> 00:36:10,226
and they've let it
run down terribly.

677
00:36:10,301 --> 00:36:12,098
But they have
a small subsidiary

678
00:36:12,170 --> 00:36:13,398
that's a real gem.

679
00:36:13,471 --> 00:36:16,440
The cannery itself is sitting
on prime waterfront land.

680
00:36:16,507 --> 00:36:19,271
So we buy the company,
close it down,

681
00:36:19,343 --> 00:36:21,937
then we sell off
the subsidiary business,

682
00:36:22,013 --> 00:36:23,378
then we sell the land.

683
00:36:24,348 --> 00:36:27,044
You ever thought of maybe
running these companies?

684
00:36:27,118 --> 00:36:29,348
There's no money
in that, Dad.

685
00:36:29,787 --> 00:36:32,449
The world has changed, Johnny.

686
00:36:33,224 --> 00:36:36,284
You wouldn't believe
how the world has changed.

687
00:36:40,531 --> 00:36:42,761
When you were a boy,
you used to go to work

688
00:36:42,833 --> 00:36:45,267
at Lockheed with me,
you remember?

689
00:36:45,603 --> 00:36:48,265
I used to separate
all the nuts and bolts.

690
00:36:48,339 --> 00:36:51,797
32 cents a day and all the
ham-and-cheese sandwiches I could eat.

691
00:36:51,876 --> 00:36:54,003
You used to say
when you grew up,

692
00:36:54,078 --> 00:36:56,171
you wanted to
work there, like me.

693
00:36:58,482 --> 00:37:01,610
Now I guess you'd just buy it
and close it down.

694
00:37:03,521 --> 00:37:04,579
You ever hear

695
00:37:04,655 --> 00:37:07,055
from any of those
old Lockheed guys, Dad?

696
00:37:07,124 --> 00:37:09,752
Rick Malinson?
Tommy Williams?

697
00:37:09,827 --> 00:37:11,419
By the time I retired,

698
00:37:11,495 --> 00:37:14,259
I was the last of us
still working there.

699
00:37:14,465 --> 00:37:16,729
They all moved out.

700
00:37:16,867 --> 00:37:19,131
To the Valley,
Palm Springs...

701
00:37:22,907 --> 00:37:24,397
My last day,

702
00:37:25,042 --> 00:37:26,304
I finished my work,

703
00:37:26,377 --> 00:37:28,868
cleaned out my locker
and went home.

704
00:37:28,946 --> 00:37:32,040
There was no one even there
to say good-bye to.

705
00:37:33,818 --> 00:37:35,308
Next morning,

706
00:37:35,386 --> 00:37:38,287
someone else doing my job
like I'd never been there.

707
00:37:41,025 --> 00:37:43,084
The world is
divided into two groups:

708
00:37:43,327 --> 00:37:44,851
workers and bosses.

709
00:37:44,929 --> 00:37:47,227
I'm a worker.
Always have been.

710
00:37:47,965 --> 00:37:49,330
I don't know, Dad, I think-

711
00:37:49,400 --> 00:37:50,697
It's okay, Johnny.

712
00:37:50,768 --> 00:37:52,531
There's nothing
wrong with it.

713
00:37:52,603 --> 00:37:54,332
I'm a worker, that's all.

714
00:37:54,505 --> 00:37:56,530
But you, you're different.

715
00:37:56,874 --> 00:37:58,808
You like to be in control.

716
00:37:58,943 --> 00:38:00,877
You like that responsibility.

717
00:38:02,046 --> 00:38:03,707
You're a boss.

718
00:38:04,515 --> 00:38:05,743
And Mom?

719
00:38:07,285 --> 00:38:08,980
What do you think?

