00:42:27,811 --> 00:42:30,302
Excuse me, senor.
You're not...

787
00:42:30,748 --> 00:42:32,841
You know, when in Rome...

788
00:42:33,517 --> 00:42:35,417
What were you
doing down in Mexico?

789
00:42:35,486 --> 00:42:36,680
Semester break.

790
00:42:36,754 --> 00:42:38,085
A bunch of kids
went down there.

791
00:42:38,155 --> 00:42:39,782
You look good.
I think you've grown.

792
00:42:39,857 --> 00:42:41,825
Dad, you say that
every time you see me.

793
00:42:41,892 --> 00:42:43,826
And I stopped
growing two years ago.

794
00:42:44,728 --> 00:42:46,093
How's your mother?

795
00:42:46,163 --> 00:42:47,596
She's fine.

796
00:42:47,665 --> 00:42:50,190
In her third year of law,
top of her class.

797
00:42:50,267 --> 00:42:51,962
It's embarrassing
when your mother

798
00:42:52,036 --> 00:42:54,061
has a higher grade point
average than you do

799
00:42:54,138 --> 00:42:55,366
but we're working that out.

800
00:42:55,439 --> 00:42:57,066
Send her my best.

801
00:42:57,541 --> 00:42:59,566
How about you?
You know? How's business?

802
00:42:59,643 --> 00:43:01,076
You know. The same.

803
00:43:01,145 --> 00:43:02,703
You win some, you lose some.

804
00:43:03,447 --> 00:43:06,245
Knowing you, I'm sure you're
winning more than you're losing.

805
00:43:06,317 --> 00:43:08,080
When you finish with that,

806
00:43:08,152 --> 00:43:10,518
you can wash it down
with a piece of cake.

807
00:43:12,756 --> 00:43:14,121
He looks really good.

808
00:43:14,258 --> 00:43:15,657
What's been going on?

809
00:43:16,927 --> 00:43:19,760
Well, we've been spending
a lot of time together.

810
00:43:19,830 --> 00:43:21,627
Quality time, huh?

811
00:43:21,765 --> 00:43:23,562
They say it's good
for parents and kids.

812
00:43:23,634 --> 00:43:26,626
Maybe you and I should spend
some more time together.

813
00:43:27,705 --> 00:43:30,799
Take it easy, Dad.
Let's not get carried away.

814
00:43:35,946 --> 00:43:37,573
This place looks
great, Grandpa.

815
00:43:37,648 --> 00:43:39,240
You've added a lot.

816
00:43:43,053 --> 00:43:44,577
You look good.

817
00:43:48,425 --> 00:43:51,155
I'm gonna name this
one after you, Bill.

818
00:45:01,965 --> 00:45:03,455
Butter, anyone?

819
00:45:03,600 --> 00:45:05,090
You want some butter, honey?

820
00:45:07,871 --> 00:45:10,032
I would like to make a toast.

821
00:45:10,107 --> 00:45:11,096
Uh-oh.

822
00:45:12,476 --> 00:45:14,535
A lot's happened
in the past two weeks.

823
00:45:14,611 --> 00:45:16,203
We've overcome
a lot of adversity,

824
00:45:16,280 --> 00:45:17,747
overcome a lot of pain.

825
00:45:17,815 --> 00:45:19,749
Pulled together as a team.

826
00:45:19,817 --> 00:45:22,377
And now we're taking
time to say thanks.

827
00:45:22,453 --> 00:45:23,715
That's beautiful, Mario.

828
00:45:23,787 --> 00:45:25,652
It's my regular
halftime speech.

829
00:45:25,723 --> 00:45:27,623
Actually,
I just wanted to say

830
00:45:27,758 --> 00:45:29,692
how happy I am to see
the family together.

831
00:45:29,760 --> 00:45:31,819
It's a thrill for me, too.
Are you finished?

832
00:45:31,895 --> 00:45:33,886
My chicken's getting cold.

833
00:45:33,964 --> 00:45:35,454
I'm finished.

834
00:45:36,266 --> 00:45:37,255
Very good.

835
00:45:37,334 --> 00:45:39,325
I'd like to make a toast.

836
00:45:40,337 --> 00:45:41,304
Hmm.

837
00:45:41,371 --> 00:45:42,736
Well, hey, Dad.

838
00:45:46,910 --> 00:45:48,639
To my lovely bride.

839
00:45:49,113 --> 00:45:50,478
Your bride?

840
00:45:52,449 --> 00:45:54,280
Did you have
a drink today, Jake?

841
00:45:54,351 --> 00:45:55,443
Before you came home, Mom,

842
00:45:55,519 --> 00:45:57,714
we had a couple of
glasses of coq au vin.

843
00:45:58,655 --> 00:46:00,486
To my lovely bride.

844
00:46:02,092 --> 00:46:05,084
Bette, you're back
in the bosom of your family,

845
00:46:05,162 --> 00:46:06,424
where you belong.

846
00:46:08,699 --> 00:46:10,462
It's good to be home.

847
00:46:11,401 --> 00:46:12,459
Hear, hear.

848
00:46:12,536 --> 00:46:13,560
Well said, Dad.

849
00:46:14,705 --> 00:46:16,332
It's good to have
everybody here, too.

850
00:46:16,406 --> 00:46:17,805
I can't remember
the last time

851
00:46:17,875 --> 00:46:19,240
we had John and
Billy together.

852
00:46:19,309 --> 00:46:20,936
Billy looks good.

853
00:46:21,011 --> 00:46:22,535
I like that earring.

854
00:46:22,679 --> 00:46:24,237
Think I should
get one of those?

855
00:46:24,314 --> 00:46:25,440
Yeah. It's very nice.

856
00:46:25,516 --> 00:46:27,484
I have a pin that goes
with that if you want.

857
00:46:27,551 --> 00:46:29,849
Oh, leave him alone, Mom.
He looks fabulous.

858
00:46:29,920 --> 00:46:31,911
I bet the girls are
falling all over themselves.

859
00:46:31,989 --> 00:46:32,978
Don't worry about me.

860
00:46:33,056 --> 00:46:34,216
This isn't at
all embarrassing.

861
00:46:34,291 --> 00:46:36,225
I hear the dorms are
co-ed now. Is that true?

862
00:46:36,293 --> 00:46:37,282
Yeah our dorm's co-ed.

863
00:46:37,361 --> 00:46:39,329
Good thing they didn't have it
when I was in school.

864
00:46:39,396 --> 00:46:41,057
I never would've got
any studying done.

865
00:46:41,131 --> 00:46:42,359
Some student you were.

866
00:46:42,432 --> 00:46:44,696
Mario was
an excellent student, Mom.

867
00:46:44,768 --> 00:46:46,929
He was a
physical education major.

868
00:46:47,004 --> 00:46:49,131
He didn't read books,
he ran laps.

869
00:46:49,206 --> 00:46:50,935
Yes, but good students
like me read books

870
00:46:51,008 --> 00:46:52,669
and ran laps
at the same time.

871
00:46:52,743 --> 00:46:54,506
Now John was a good student.

872
00:46:54,578 --> 00:46:55,602
Thank you, Mommy.

873
00:46:55,679 --> 00:46:56,839
From kindergarten on,

874
00:46:56,914 --> 00:46:59,007
every Saturday we'd
go to the library.

875
00:46:59,082 --> 00:47:00,071
Get out four books.

876
00:47:00,150 --> 00:47:01,708
You'd read them,
we'd go back,

877
00:47:01,785 --> 00:47:03,309
get out another four books.

878
00:47:03,387 --> 00:47:05,446
It worked, too.
I learned how to read.

879
00:47:05,522 --> 00:47:06,750
You did more than that.

880
00:47:06,824 --> 00:47:07,984
So how does it work?

881
00:47:08,058 --> 00:47:10,356
Are the girls on another
floor? How do you find them?

882
00:47:10,427 --> 00:47:12,588
Somebody hose this man down.

883
00:47:16,033 --> 00:47:18,263
What is it, Dad?
What's the matter?

884
00:47:21,872 --> 00:47:23,362
I'm just happy.

885
00:47:29,947 --> 00:47:32,006
Let's try to make it easy
for Grandma and Grandpa

886
00:47:32,082 --> 00:47:33,606
while you're here. Okay?

887
00:47:33,684 --> 00:47:35,208
Sure, you get so used
to hearing it,

888
00:47:35,285 --> 00:47:36,752
you don't even
realize it's on.

889
00:47:36,820 --> 00:47:38,117
It was on, believe me.

890
00:47:38,255 --> 00:47:39,586
My fillings are
still rattling.

891
00:47:39,656 --> 00:47:40,816
Sorry.

892
00:47:42,159 --> 00:47:44,354
So when do you have
to be back at school?

893
00:47:44,428 --> 00:47:46,521
I don't know.
I may not go back to school.

894
00:47:46,597 --> 00:47:48,531
I'm thinking of
going back down to Mexico

895
00:47:48,599 --> 00:47:50,294
to live for a while.

896
00:47:50,367 --> 00:47:51,959
What's the big attraction
with Mexico?

897
00:47:52,035 --> 00:47:54,128
All the people in Mexico
are trying to come here.

898
00:47:54,204 --> 00:47:55,432
Did you know that?

899
00:47:55,505 --> 00:47:57,871
A lot of kids from school
are down there.

900
00:47:57,941 --> 00:47:59,465
They've got
a little community going.

901
00:47:59,543 --> 00:48:01,033
It's, uh, it's fun.

902
00:48:04,514 --> 00:48:06,482
Okay, it's fun,
but believe it or not,

903
00:48:06,617 --> 00:48:08,585
you may want
a job someday, Bill.

904
00:48:08,652 --> 00:48:10,085
Lying on the beach in Mexico

905
00:48:10,153 --> 00:48:12,553
is not going to help prepare
you for anything.

906
00:48:12,623 --> 00:48:14,784
Unless you want to
be a mariachi singer,

907
00:48:14,925 --> 00:48:17,120
in which case
it's a work-study program.

908
00:48:17,194 --> 00:48:18,889
I could say
I went to college.

909
00:48:18,962 --> 00:48:21,294
Nobody checks.
I'll say I have a B.A.

910
00:48:22,165 --> 00:48:23,530
I'll say I have a PhD.

911
00:48:23,600 --> 00:48:24,897
Might as well do it right.

912
00:48:24,968 --> 00:48:26,333
Two PHDs.

913
00:48:26,470 --> 00:48:27,835
One in chemistry,
one in physics.

914
00:48:27,905 --> 00:48:30,806
I have to go back to New York
soon, and I'd like this settled.

915
00:48:30,874 --> 00:48:31,932
What's your mother think?

916
00:48:32,009 --> 00:48:34,443
She said I should use
my best judgment.

917
00:48:34,511 --> 00:48:36,308
I'm not sure how
I feel about this.

918
00:48:36,380 --> 00:48:38,371
We should talk
about this a little bit.

919
00:48:38,448 --> 00:48:40,075
I- I don't see why.

920
00:48:40,584 --> 00:48:42,518
We haven't talked
about it up until now,

921
00:48:42,586 --> 00:48:43,985
and I think
I know what I want.

922
00:48:44,054 --> 00:48:46,420
Johnny, something's wrong.

923
00:48:47,391 --> 00:48:49,882
Would you come
here and take a look?

924
00:49:02,339 --> 00:49:03,636
That'll be all for now,
Mr. Tremont.

925
00:49:03,707 --> 00:49:05,504
You can get dressed
if you like.

926
00:49:05,575 --> 00:49:06,633
Is he all right?

927
00:49:06,777 --> 00:49:07,835
Yes, he's fine.

928
00:49:07,911 --> 00:49:09,105
It's a very
painful procedure.

929
00:49:09,179 --> 00:49:10,237
No getting around it.

930
00:49:10,314 --> 00:49:11,975
Any idea what
the problem might be?

931
00:49:12,049 --> 00:49:13,607
Could be any of
a number of things.

932
00:49:13,684 --> 00:49:15,379
I suspect small growths
in his bladder.

933
00:49:15,452 --> 00:49:16,942
The question is,
are they malignant?

934
00:49:17,020 --> 00:49:19,284
Will the tests you've
just done tell you that?

935
00:49:19,356 --> 00:49:20,823
Not completely.

936
00:49:20,891 --> 00:49:23,257
The fact they're bleeding
is not a good sign.

937
00:49:23,727 --> 00:49:25,627
So this is serious?

938
00:49:26,229 --> 00:49:29,528
Yes. I think we should schedule
him for exploratory surgery.

939
00:49:33,103 --> 00:49:34,127
If it were serious, Dad,

940
00:49:34,204 --> 00:49:35,933
they wouldn't have
let you out of there.

941
00:49:36,006 --> 00:49:37,530
They would've
cut you right open

942
00:49:37,607 --> 00:49:39,165
and operated on the spot.

943
00:49:39,242 --> 00:49:40,800
I wouldn't be
surprised at all

944
00:49:40,877 --> 00:49:41,866
if it were just a cyst.

945
00:49:43,313 --> 00:49:45,679
Just a cyst? Right.

946
00:49:46,116 --> 00:49:48,175
I don't even think
it's worth telling Mom about.

947
00:49:48,251 --> 00:49:50,082
Why worry her for nothing?

948
00:49:50,153 --> 00:49:52,178
Whatever you say, Johnny.

949
00:49:53,890 --> 00:49:55,255
You're the boss.

950
00:50:01,531 --> 00:50:02,930
He told you, didn't he?

951
00:50:03,066 --> 00:50:04,465
Of course, he told me.

952
00:50:04,534 --> 00:50:06,365
Well, then you know
it's nothing serious.

953
00:50:06,436 --> 00:50:07,698
If it wasn't serious,

954
00:50:07,771 --> 00:50:09,602
you'd have told me
about it yourself.

955
00:50:09,673 --> 00:50:12,403
Look, Mom, you're supposed
to avoid any stress right now.

956
00:50:12,476 --> 00:50:14,603
I was afraid you might
get upset about nothing.

957
00:50:14,678 --> 00:50:15,906
That's why I didn't tell you.

958
00:50:15,979 --> 00:50:18,846
I'm sorry. Maybe I was wrong, but
that's what I was trying to do.

959
00:50:18,915 --> 00:50:20,906
He says it's just a cyst.

960
00:50:20,984 --> 00:50:21,951
That's right.

961
00:50:22,019 --> 00:50:23,884
That's a fairly
simple procedure.

962
00:50:23,954 --> 00:50:25,012
Yes, it is.

963
00:50:25,088 --> 00:50:27,181
Mother, I'd tell you
if there was anything wrong.

964
00:50:27,257 --> 00:50:28,781
I would.

965
00:50:29,493 --> 00:50:30,619
Okay.

966
00:50:41,838 --> 00:50:43,772
Do I walk around
like this, John,

967
00:50:43,907 --> 00:50:45,875
with the back open
and all the nurses here?

968
00:50:45,942 --> 00:50:47,967
Yeah. It says right here
on the admission slip,

969
00:50:48,045 --> 00:50:49,842
"Dress is informal. "

970
00:50:49,913 --> 00:50:51,312
There you go.

971
00:50:51,548 --> 00:50:52,845
You need to sign this, Dad.

972
00:50:52,916 --> 00:50:54,178
What is it?

973
00:50:54,251 --> 00:50:56,116
It just says if
anything happens to you,

974
00:50:56,186 --> 00:50:57,744
I get your catcher's mitt.

975
00:50:57,821 --> 00:50:59,846
I don't have
a catcher's mitt.

976
00:50:59,923 --> 00:51:01,515
Sorry. Bad joke.

977
00:51:01,892 --> 00:51:04,417
Dr. Santana
ordered this medication.

978
00:51:04,995 --> 00:51:07,156
It's just something
to relax you.

979
00:51:07,497 --> 00:51:10,432
If you have any left over,
I'd like a little.

980
00:51:17,174 --> 00:51:19,938
Guess you have to pay extra
to get one with a personality.

981
00:51:20,010 --> 00:51:21,602
What time is it?

982
00:51:22,446 --> 00:51:23,845
About noon.

983
00:51:25,048 --> 00:51:26,106
Not much longer.

984
00:51:26,183 --> 00:51:27,411
Nope.

985
00:51:28,819 --> 00:51:30,184
Is this comfortable
for you, Dad?

986
00:51:30,253 --> 00:51:31,550
Fine.

987
00:51:31,988 --> 00:51:33,785
I'm gonna let you rest now.

988
00:51:33,857 --> 00:51:36,087
That stuff's gonna
really mellow you out.

989
00:51:36,159 --> 00:51:37,148
Okay.

990
00:51:37,727 --> 00:51:39,592
Don't forget,
if you need anything,

991
00:51:39,663 --> 00:51:41,324
just ring the buzzer here.

992
00:51:46,703 --> 00:51:48,671
I guess this is it, huh?

993
00:51:50,907 --> 00:51:52,704
You're gonna be okay.

994
00:51:54,044 --> 00:51:56,706
You know, John,
I see men now,

995
00:51:57,881 --> 00:51:59,143
they hug.

996
00:52:00,884 --> 00:52:02,647
We've never hugged.

997
00:52:05,722 --> 00:52:07,553
Wanna give it a try?

998
00:52:08,825 --> 00:52:09,951
I do.

999
00:52:24,841 --> 00:52:26,570
I love you, Johnny.

1000
00:52:28,311 --> 00:52:30,438
I love you, too, Dad.

1001
00:52:31,982 --> 00:52:34,507
Well, Mr. Tremont,
I'm afraid it's cancer.

1002
00:52:38,188 --> 00:52:39,314
Cancer.

1003
00:52:39,389 --> 00:52:41,448
Yes. There were
several malignant tumors.

1004
00:52:41,525 --> 00:52:43,356
I think I got 'em,
but we have to do

1005
00:52:43,460 --> 00:52:45,325
some chemotherapy.
We won't radiate.

1006
00:52:45,395 --> 00:52:47,920
Not with a man with
your father's age.

1007
00:52:47,998 --> 00:52:49,829
Maybe this is
a silly question,

1008
00:52:49,900 --> 00:52:51,265
but are you absolutely sure?

1009
00:52:51,334 --> 00:52:52,392
Yes.

1010
00:52:52,903 --> 00:52:54,666
A virulent form, too.
It's a good thing

1011
00:52:54,738 --> 00:52:56,467
we went in
and got it when we did.

1012
00:52:56,540 --> 00:52:58,303
Listen, Dr. Santana.

1013
00:52:58,708 --> 00:53:00,005
Whatever you do,

1014
00:53:00,076 --> 00:53:02,169
don't mention
cancer to my father.

1015
00:53:02,345 --> 00:53:05,280
He's terribly anxious and
frightened about that word.

1016
00:53:05,348 --> 00:53:07,009
It's beyond
anything rational.

1017
00:53:07,083 --> 00:53:08,448
Calm down, Mr. Tremont.

1018
00:53:08,518 --> 00:53:11,009
You'd be surprised what these
older people can take.

1019
00:53:11,087 --> 00:53:12,952
Their children tend
to underestimate them.

1020
00:53:13,023 --> 00:53:15,150
I don't
underestimate him, Doctor.

1021
00:53:15,392 --> 00:53:18,293
I want to be the one
to tell him, that's all.

1022
00:53:19,396 --> 00:53:21,261
It's cancer, isn't it?

1023
00:53:21,331 --> 00:53:22,821
Mom, I told you.

1024
00:53:22,899 --> 00:53:25,367
It's a cyst and they
took it out. That's all.

1025
00:53:25,535 --> 00:53:27,366
I want to go see him.

1026
00:53:27,437 --> 00:53:28,768
Mom!

1027
00:53:29,839 --> 00:53:32,399
Mom, you can't go
see him right now.

1028
00:53:33,210 --> 00:53:34,472
Will you
listen to me?

1029
00:53:34,544 --> 00:53:37,342
You can't expose yourself
to that kind of stress.

1030
00:53:37,414 --> 00:53:39,575
If he was all right,
you'd let me see him.

1031
00:53:39,649 --> 00:53:40,877
Oh, come on, Mom.

1032
00:53:40,951 --> 00:53:43,215
John's only thinking about
what's best for you.

1033
00:53:43,286 --> 00:53:44,412
You know that.

1034
00:53:44,487 --> 00:53:46,978
You got to listen to him,
Mom. Come on.

1035
00:53:48,258 --> 00:53:50,453
This is my husband
and I'm gonna see him.

1036
00:53:50,527 --> 00:53:52,893
Now, either you're gonna
drive me or I'm gonna walk,

1037
00:53:52,963 --> 00:53:54,453
but I'm goin'.

1038
00:54:01,137 --> 00:54:02,627
Dad?
What is it?

1039
00:54:02,706 --> 00:54:03,832
What's out there?

1040
00:54:03,907 --> 00:54:05,932
There's nothing, Dad.
You're in the hospital.

1041
00:54:06,009 --> 00:54:07,874
It's fine.
There's nothing the matter.

1042
00:54:09,045 --> 00:54:11,138
Billy, go get
Dr. Santana right now.

1043
00:54:11,214 --> 00:54:13,273
Just do it!

1044
00:54:13,350 --> 00:54:14,476
Get her out of here.

1045
00:54:14,551 --> 00:54:15,609
What's the matter
with him?

1046
00:54:15,685 --> 00:54:17,152
Jake, it's me!

1047
00:54:17,220 --> 00:54:19,085
Why doesn't he know me? Jake!

1048
00:54:20,323 --> 00:54:22,154
Mr. Tremont, I'm Dr. Santana.

1049
00:54:22,225 --> 00:54:23,214
Do you know who I am?

1050
00:54:23,293 --> 00:54:26,956
I'm fine.
I'm just fine, thank you.

1051
00:54:27,030 --> 00:54:29,396
He's in shock.
Give him 25 mg Librium IM

1052
00:54:29,466 --> 00:54:31,127
and check his vitals
every two hours.

1053
00:54:31,201 --> 00:54:32,133
Yes, Doctor.

1054
00:54:32,202 --> 00:54:33,999
This is fairly standard
with older people.

1055
00:54:34,070 --> 00:54:36,334
They often go into delayed
shock even after minor surgery.

1056
00:54:36,406 --> 00:54:37,566
This is standard?

1057
00:54:37,641 --> 00:54:39,575
Do you have any idea
what happened in there?

1058
00:54:39,643 --> 00:54:41,838
I'm sure it was a frightening
experience for you,

1059
00:54:41,911 --> 00:54:43,242
but what you got to
understand is

1060
00:54:43,313 --> 00:54:46,077
that what we're dealing with here
actually is a form of senility.

1061
00:54:46,149 --> 00:54:47,741
He wasn't senile
when he came in.

1062
00:54:47,817 --> 00:54:49,546
Why should he
suddenly go into senility?

1063
00:54:49,619 --> 00:54:51,849
Senility is a very strange
thing. It comes and goes.

1064
00:54:51,921 --> 00:54:54,287
You get a stress situation
like this and it just crops up.

1065
00:54:54,357 --> 00:54:56,257
I'm sure, with proper
rest and medication,

1066
00:54:56,326 --> 00:54:58,157
the situation
will correct itself.

1067
00:54:58,228 --> 00:54:59,422
What do we do
in the meantime?

1068
00:54:59,496 --> 00:55:00,463
Nothing.

1069
00:55:00,530 --> 00:55:01,997
What do you mean
"nothing"?

1070
00:55:02,065 --> 00:55:03,896
No tests, no consultations?
We just wait?

1071
00:55:03,967 --> 00:55:06,265
We wait for him to respond
to the medication.

1072
00:55:06,503 --> 00:55:08,334
He'll be fine. Don't worry.

1073
00:55:08,872 --> 00:55:11,466
Did you tell my father
he has cancer?

1074
00:55:15,779 --> 00:55:17,440
You have to understand,
Mr. Tremont,

1075
00:55:17,514 --> 00:55:19,448
I have an ethical obligation
to my patients.

1076
00:55:19,516 --> 00:55:21,381
He had a right to know.

1077
00:55:23,887 --> 00:55:26,720
I'm not quite sure what it is
you want me to do, Mr. Tremont.

1078
00:55:26,790 --> 00:55:28,087
Dr. Ethridge,

1079
00:55:28,158 --> 00:55:31,616
I don't have a lot of
confidence in Santana.

1080
00:55:32,595 --> 00:55:34,654
And you're
the hospital administrator,

1081
00:55:34,731 --> 00:55:36,426
and I just want you
to know

1082
00:55:36,499 --> 00:55:38,490
that this
doesn't feel right.

1083
00:55:38,568 --> 00:55:40,536
Dr. Santana is
a fine young surgeon.

1084
00:55:40,603 --> 00:55:42,594
It seems to me that
he's been very thorough

1085
00:55:42,672 --> 00:55:44,606
and professional in
your father's case.

1086
00:55:44,674 --> 00:55:46,369
I told him not
to say anything

1087
00:55:46,476 --> 00:55:47,602
about cancer to my father

1088
00:55:47,677 --> 00:55:49,941
because he's very
frightened by that word.

1089
00:55:50,080 --> 00:55:52,344
He went ahead
and told him anyway.

1090
00:55:52,582 --> 00:55:55,016
Well, it's always
a difficult call for a doctor.

1091
00:55:55,085 --> 00:55:57,315
He has to balance
the will of the family members

1092
00:55:57,387 --> 00:55:59,150
with the patient's right
to know.

1093
00:55:59,222 --> 00:56:00,746
I'm sure he had no choice.

1094
00:56:00,824 --> 00:56:02,086
He had a choice.

1095
00:56:02,158 --> 00:56:03,750
He could have listened to me.

1096
00:56:03,827 --> 00:56:05,124
I know my father.

1097
00:56:05,195 --> 00:56:06,753
And what's happening
to him right now

1098
00:56:06,830 --> 00:56:07,922
is a direct result

1099
00:56:07,997 --> 00:56:09,988
of Dr. Santana's
poor judgment.

1100
00:56:21,010 --> 00:56:22,739
Why did you
strap his arms down?

1101
00:56:22,812 --> 00:56:24,609
To keep him from
hurting himself.

1102
00:56:24,681 --> 00:56:27,946
He's been flailing around
pretty good with those hands.

1103
00:56:28,017 --> 00:56:30,850
Yeah, well, I'm his son and I
say he doesn't need these things.

1104
00:56:30,920 --> 00:56:32,649
Give us a call
when you're ready,

1105
00:56:32,722 --> 00:56:33,950
and we'll put
him back in bed.

1106
00:56:34,023 --> 00:56:35,786
I don't believe it.

1107
00:56:36,059 --> 00:56:37,822
Hey, dad,
how you doin'?

1108
00:56:38,495 --> 00:56:40,759
What is it? Does he
always look like this?

1109
00:56:40,830 --> 00:56:42,923
Look, hey, look,
look, I've brought Annie.

1110
00:56:42,999 --> 00:56:44,796
And I got
Billy here. Huh?

1111
00:56:44,868 --> 00:56:45,857
Hey, Dad.

1112
00:56:46,302 --> 00:56:48,293
How are you
feelin', Dad?

1113
00:56:48,605 --> 00:56:49,799
Can you hear me?

1114
00:56:49,873 --> 00:56:52,774
Hey, Grandpa, it's me, Billy.
How you doin'?

1115
00:56:53,810 --> 00:56:56,643
God, John, I can't stand
to see him looking like this.

1116
00:56:56,713 --> 00:56:59,147
What is it, Dad?
What's the matter?

1117
00:57:12,962 --> 00:57:16,227
That would be
absolutely adequate, I think.

1118
00:57:16,800 --> 00:57:19,064
I gave him a sedative.
That should calm him down.

1119
00:57:19,135 --> 00:57:20,363
How long had he
been like that?

1120
00:57:20,437 --> 00:57:22,530
The whole time we've been
here. At least half an hour.

1121
00:57:22,639 --> 00:57:24,106
Did he seem
depressed?

1122
00:57:24,174 --> 00:57:25,232
Jesus, Doctor.

1123
00:57:25,308 --> 00:57:27,003
It's a good thing
you're not a detective.

1124
00:57:27,076 --> 00:57:28,304
Yeah, he seemed
depressed.

1125
00:57:28,378 --> 00:57:30,278
What the hell do you
think is going on here?

1126
00:57:30,346 --> 00:57:32,041
I meant more than usual,
Mr. Tremont.

1127
00:57:32,115 --> 00:57:35,380
He's been sliding every day since
he's been in here. And you know that.

1128
00:57:35,452 --> 00:57:36,441
Mr. Tremont-

1129
00:57:36,519 --> 00:57:38,646
You're not gonna tell me
that this is normal behavior.

1130
00:57:38,721 --> 00:57:41,451
This particular manifestation
of the depression is unusual,

1131
00:57:41,524 --> 00:57:43,549
true, but the sedative
will bring him around.

1132
00:57:43,626 --> 00:57:45,218
A sedative?
The man is hallucinating.

1133
00:57:45,295 --> 00:57:46,694
He's crying nonstop.

1134
00:57:46,763 --> 00:57:48,628
He doesn't recognize
anyone in his family,

1135
00:57:48,698 --> 00:57:50,529
and you're
giving him a sedative?

1136
00:57:50,600 --> 00:57:52,568
And why didn't you give him
some Sucrets, too?

1137
00:57:52,635 --> 00:57:54,296
Maybe he has a sore
throat you can fix!

1138
00:57:54,370 --> 00:57:56,531
We've scheduled your father
for release tomorrow.

1139
00:57:56,606 --> 00:57:58,335
You can pick him
up anytime after 12:00.

1140
00:57:58,408 --> 00:57:59,875
What do you mean,
"release"?

1141
00:57:59,943 --> 00:58:02,070
Are you trying to tell me that
my father has recovered?

1142
00:58:02,145 --> 00:58:04,136
Well, no, of course not,
but medically speaking

1143
00:58:04,214 --> 00:58:05,841
there's nothing more
we can do for him.

1144
00:58:05,915 --> 00:58:07,041
We cannot hold
hospital beds

1145
00:58:07,116 --> 00:58:09,209
for patients who cannot
profit from medical care.

1146
00:58:09,285 --> 00:58:10,309
How would we know?

1147
00:58:10,386 --> 00:58:11,876
He's never gotten
any medical care!

1148
00:58:11,955 --> 00:58:13,445
You have to understand,
Mr. Tremont,

1149
00:58:13,523 --> 00:58:15,787
while his condition is stable,
basically he's custodial.

1150
00:58:15,859 --> 00:58:16,951
What exactly
does that mean?

1151
00:58:17,026 --> 00:58:18,220
I'll tell you
what that means.

1152
00:58:18,294 --> 00:58:20,455
That means they don't give
a shit if he lives or dies.

1153
00:58:20,530 --> 00:58:22,395
He's not custodial!
God damn it!

1154
00:58:22,465 --> 00:58:24,490
What kind of word is that
to describe a person?

1155
00:58:24,567 --> 00:58:25,556
I don't think-

1156
00:58:25,635 --> 00:58:26,602
Just calm down.

1157
00:58:26,669 --> 00:58:28,034
You want my father
out of here?

1158
00:58:28,104 --> 00:58:29,366
Well, let me tell you
something.

1159
00:58:29,439 --> 00:58:31,134
I want him out of here
more than you do.

1160
00:58:31,207 --> 00:58:33,004
You're not good enough
to take care of him.

1161
00:58:33,076 --> 00:58:34,134
John,
what are you doing?

1162
00:58:34,210 --> 00:58:35,575
Mr. Tremont-
Don't you touch him.

1163
00:58:35,645 --> 00:58:36,942
This is
very unnecessary.

1164
00:58:37,013 --> 00:58:38,571
I said I'm taking him home.

1165
00:58:38,648 --> 00:58:40,946
Mr. Tremont,
this is very unfortunate.

1166
00:59:04,274 --> 00:59:05,969
What do we do now?

1167
00:59:06,743 --> 00:59:08,233
I don't know.

1168
00:59:08,444 --> 00:59:09,809
We may have no choice
but to-

1169
00:59:09,879 --> 00:59:11,176
No, I don't want
to do that.

1170
00:59:11,247 --> 00:59:12,942
I don't wanna put
him in a nursing home.

1171
00:59:13,016 --> 00:59:15,416
I don't either, John,
but we have to do something.

1172
00:59:15,518 --> 00:59:17,349
If you take Mom
out to your place,

1173
00:59:17,420 --> 00:59:19,217
I'll take care
of Dad at home.

1174
00:59:19,289 --> 00:59:20,483
Wait a second, John.

1175
00:59:20,557 --> 00:59:22,218
You can't handle
him in this condition.

1176
00:59:22,292 --> 00:59:23,486
I think
I can do it.

1177
00:59:23,560 --> 00:59:25,152
I can do better
than the hospital did.

1178
00:59:25,228 --> 00:59:26,217
I can stay and help.

1179
00:59:26,296 --> 00:59:27,263
No.

1180
00:59:27,330 --> 00:59:28,456
Why not?

1181
00:59:28,531 --> 00:59:30,123
I'll take care of him.
He's my father.

1182
00:59:30,199 --> 00:59:31,257
Well, he's my grandfather.

1183
00:59:31,334 --> 00:59:32,358
And I'm
your father.

1184
00:59:32,435 --> 00:59:34,426
Great. Now that we
know who everyone is,

1185
00:59:34,504 --> 00:59:36,495
can we talk about
what's best for this man?

1186
00:59:36,639 --> 00:59:38,300
I don't want you
here right now, Billy.

1187
00:59:38,374 --> 00:59:40,001
You don't have to see this.

1188
00:59:40,076 --> 00:59:41,543
Dad, I am not a kid.

1189
00:59:41,611 --> 00:59:42,737
Look,
I want you gone.

1190
00:59:42,812 --> 00:59:44,871
Go back to school,
go back to Mexico.

1191
00:59:44,948 --> 00:59:46,176
You're
in the way here.

1192
00:59:46,249 --> 00:59:47,614
Don't you
understand?

1193
00:59:48,918 --> 00:59:50,647
Yeah, I understand.

1194
01:00:00,897 --> 01:00:02,762
I want to
talk to him.

1195
01:00:02,932 --> 01:00:04,695
It's not a good
idea now, Mom, really.

1196
01:00:04,767 --> 01:00:06,064
Annie's right,
Mom.

1197
01:00:06,202 --> 01:00:07,533
Come on,
get in the hearse.

1198
01:00:07,604 --> 01:00:09,663
You'd like that,
wouldn't you, Mario?

1199
01:00:09,739 --> 01:00:11,297
I meant "get in the car,"
Mom.

1200
01:00:11,374 --> 01:00:13,467
It was
a slip of the tongue.

1201
01:00:22,885 --> 01:00:26,116
Okay, Mom, okay. Come on,
come on. He'll be all right.

1202
01:00:26,189 --> 01:00:27,178
He'll be all right.

1203
01:00:27,256 --> 01:00:28,883
John's gonna
take care of him.

1204
01:00:30,893 --> 01:00:32,554
Here we go, Dad.

1205
01:00:35,365 --> 01:00:37,162
We got a score yet? Huh?

1206
01:00:39,135 --> 01:00:41,228
This kid Gooden is fabulous,
isn't he?

1207
01:00:41,304 --> 01:00:43,067
He kind of reminds
me of Bob Gibson.

1208
01:00:43,139 --> 01:00:45,232
You know,
a real competitor.

1209
01:00:52,515 --> 01:00:55,075
What is that?
Did you get that, Dad?

1210
01:00:57,620 --> 01:00:58,985
All right.

1211
01:01:00,723 --> 01:01:02,122
Here we go.

1212
01:01:04,594 --> 01:01:05,993
A club soda.

1213
01:01:10,733 --> 01:01:13,463
Well, we've got to work
on your technique here.

1214
01:01:14,637 --> 01:01:16,264
That's all right.

1215
01:01:18,708 --> 01:01:21,802
A little home-cooked meal,
that's what you need.

1216
01:01:23,379 --> 01:01:25,370
Remember how you
used to tell me

1217
01:01:25,515 --> 01:01:27,540
that all
the great chefs were men?

1218
01:01:28,084 --> 01:01:29,642
Well, I think
you're right.

1219
01:01:29,719 --> 01:01:31,311
Wait till you
taste this.

1220
01:01:33,222 --> 01:01:34,689
Come on, Dad.

1221
01:01:36,159 --> 01:01:37,592
All right.

1222
01:01:38,561 --> 01:01:40,791
What's that?
Too big, you say?

1223
01:01:40,963 --> 01:01:42,225
Hmm, all right.

1224
01:01:42,732 --> 01:01:44,324
Here. Try this.

1225
01:01:46,903 --> 01:01:48,962
Come on, Dad,
take a bite.

1226
01:01:49,572 --> 01:01:51,767
Come on,
there you go.

1227
01:01:52,208 --> 01:01:54,699
All right!
We have a sale here.

1228
01:01:55,478 --> 01:01:57,776
Well.
Let's push our luck.

1229
01:01:59,015 --> 01:02:01,415
Here. Wash it down
with this, Dad.

1230
01:02:03,820 --> 01:02:06,789
Dad, don't bite the glassware.
House rules.

1231
01:02:10,393 --> 01:02:13,226
You just didn't like
that place, did you?

1232
01:02:13,596 --> 01:02:15,086
Neither did I.

1233
01:02:16,966 --> 01:02:18,991
Here you go. One more bite.

1234
01:02:21,704 --> 01:02:24,070
There you go, Dad.
All right!

1235
01:02:26,709 --> 01:02:28,643
We're going
to be okay, huh.

1236
01:02:29,879 --> 01:02:32,177
Here you go, Pop.
That's better.

1237
01:02:34,484 --> 01:02:36,076
All right, Dad.

1238
01:02:36,385 --> 01:02:37,852
Hang on a second here

1239
01:02:37,920 --> 01:02:40,150
and I'll have you
all settled in.

1240
01:02:42,558 --> 01:02:44,685
Let me grab these
and I'll be right back.

1241
01:02:44,761 --> 01:02:46,092
Why are we here, Ed?

1242
01:02:46,162 --> 01:02:47,424
Why aren't we
at the farm?

1243
01:02:47,497 --> 01:02:48,486
What?

1244
01:02:48,564 --> 01:02:51,260
You know they'll be
mad at us if we stay,

1245
01:02:51,334 --> 01:02:52,323
you know that.

1246
01:02:52,735 --> 01:02:54,999
Where's
the owner of the house?

1247
01:02:55,471 --> 01:02:58,201
This is your house, Dad.
What are you talking about?

1248
01:02:58,274 --> 01:03:00,504
Mandy is out of
the pasture again, Ed.

1249
01:03:00,576 --> 01:03:02,441
I'm worried about her.

1250
01:03:05,214 --> 01:03:08,513
Well, don't worry, Dad.
I'm-I'm sure she's okay.

1251
01:03:08,584 --> 01:03:09,881
You think so?

1252
01:03:10,553 --> 01:03:11,884
I do.

1253
01:03:12,555 --> 01:03:15,547
Hand me that 18 wrench there,
by the chicken wire.

1254
01:03:36,979 --> 01:03:39,038
That ought to hold it now.

1255
01:03:40,750 --> 01:03:41,910
Look.

1256
01:03:54,831 --> 01:03:57,925
A good night's sleep
is what we need here, Dad.

1257
01:03:58,367 --> 01:04:00,130
Isn't that's what
you always used to say

1258
01:04:00,203 --> 01:04:01,830
when we had a problem?

1259
01:04:03,306 --> 01:04:05,069
"Let's sleep on it. "

1260
01:04:08,444 --> 01:04:11,072
Well, we got
ourselves a problem here, Dad.

1261
01:04:11,147 --> 01:04:12,808
Let's sleep on it.

1262
01:05:03,566 --> 01:05:04,726
Dad?

1263
01:05:09,805 --> 01:05:10,794
Dad?

1264
01:05:13,609 --> 01:05:14,598
Dad?

1265
01:05:19,582 --> 01:05:21,345
Dad, where are you?

1266
01:05:23,586 --> 01:05:24,575
Dad?

1267
01:05:41,904 --> 01:05:42,893
Dad?

1268
01:05:48,911 --> 01:05:49,900
Dad?

1269
01:06:08,464 --> 01:06:09,453
Dad?

1270
01:06:10,366 --> 01:06:11,799
What the hell
are you doing?

1271
01:06:12,735 --> 01:06:14,464
Oh, Dad, here,
let me help you.

1272
01:06:17,473 --> 01:06:19,168
All right, all right.
It's okay.

1273
01:06:20,309 --> 01:06:21,333
Come here, Pop,
come here.

1274
01:06:21,410 --> 01:06:22,399
No.

1275
01:06:24,080 --> 01:06:25,411
Ouch! Ow!

1276
01:06:28,017 --> 01:06:30,383
Dad,
I'm gonna lift the bed.

1277
01:06:32,021 --> 01:06:33,352
Crawl out.

1278
01:06:35,257 --> 01:06:37,248
Come on, Dad, crawl out.

1279
01:06:37,693 --> 01:06:39,251
Dad, come on.

1280
01:07:02,084 --> 01:07:05,383
Okay, now. I've got you.

1281
01:07:07,690 --> 01:07:09,055
Shh.

1282
01:07:11,260 --> 01:07:12,488
Come on.

1283
01:07:15,731 --> 01:07:16,925
Shh.

1284
01:07:17,867 --> 01:07:20,700
I got you, Dad.
It's all right. It's okay.

1285
01:07:23,773 --> 01:07:26,037
Shh. I got you, I got you.

1286
01:07:26,108 --> 01:07:27,097
I got you.

1287
01:07:36,052 --> 01:07:37,485
Mr. Tremont?

1288
01:07:38,687 --> 01:07:40,416
I understand you
put your father back

1289
01:07:40,489 --> 01:07:42,423
in the hospital.
I'm very sorry.

1290
01:07:42,491 --> 01:07:43,480
Yeah.

1291
01:07:43,826 --> 01:07:45,453
I thought it might
be difficult for you

1292
01:07:45,528 --> 01:07:46,927
to care for him
at home.

1293
01:07:46,996 --> 01:07:49,021
It's really not the place
for him right now.

1294
01:07:49,098 --> 01:07:51,965
Well, he can't be at home
and he can't be here, right?

1295
01:07:52,034 --> 01:07:55,526
Maybe he can just hover
overhead in a helicopter.

1296
01:07:56,238 --> 01:07:58,263
It's very hard,
I realize

1297
01:07:58,340 --> 01:08:00,570
for children
to understand

1298
01:08:00,643 --> 01:08:02,474
that their parents
have gotten old.

1299
01:08:03,245 --> 01:08:05,338
To know what
that really means.

1300
01:08:05,414 --> 01:08:07,882
I know what that means,
to be old. It means

1301
01:08:07,950 --> 01:08:10,646
most people would
rather you were dead.

1302
01:08:10,853 --> 01:08:14,152
Mr. Tremont, you have to understand
that doctors are only human, too.

1303
01:08:14,223 --> 01:08:15,520
We can't solve every problem.

1304
01:08:15,591 --> 01:08:17,684
We can't save every patient.

1305
01:08:18,461 --> 01:08:21,555
We work in a system where
old people tend to sometimes

1306
01:08:21,630 --> 01:08:22,961
fall through the cracks.

1307
01:08:23,032 --> 01:08:24,863
What is it you want?

1308
01:08:25,101 --> 01:08:26,762
Why are you here?

1309
01:08:27,470 --> 01:08:29,665
There's another doctor
here at the hospital.

1310
01:08:29,738 --> 01:08:32,571
I think he might be
better than Dr. Santana.

1311
01:08:32,641 --> 01:08:33,767
What?

1312
01:08:34,110 --> 01:08:35,907
I'll deny ever
having said that.

1313
01:08:35,978 --> 01:08:37,502
He's a fine man.

1314
01:08:37,780 --> 01:08:39,304
I'd like to see
if I can get him

1315
01:08:39,381 --> 01:08:41,042
to take a look
at your father.

1316
01:08:43,352 --> 01:08:44,751
Mr. Tremont?

1317
01:08:45,921 --> 01:08:47,320
Mr. Tremont?

1318
01:08:49,325 --> 01:08:51,316
How are you,
Mr. Tremont?

1319
01:08:52,695 --> 01:08:54,890
Let's get a few more studies.

1320
01:08:55,397 --> 01:08:59,390
Please order an EEG and let's look
for any metabolic abnormalities.

1321
01:08:59,468 --> 01:09:02,995
Order calcium-magnesium
and liver function tests.

1322
01:09:07,610 --> 01:09:09,840
I'm not sure
exactly what caused it,

1323
01:09:09,912 --> 01:09:11,709
but right now,
I'm inclined to go along

1324
01:09:11,780 --> 01:09:13,509
with the diagnosis
of a seizure.

1325
01:09:13,582 --> 01:09:15,914
The question is,
what caused it?

1326
01:09:16,218 --> 01:09:18,311
And why is he still comatose?

1327
01:09:18,387 --> 01:09:21,117
If you want to have
another consultation on this,

1328
01:09:21,190 --> 01:09:22,657
please do so.

1329
01:09:26,128 --> 01:09:27,755
No, that
won't be necessary.

1330
01:09:27,830 --> 01:09:29,024
Well, having said that

1331
01:09:29,098 --> 01:09:30,998
don't get the impression
that we're going to

1332
01:09:31,066 --> 01:09:32,556
sit by and do nothing.

1333
01:09:32,635 --> 01:09:33,829
We won't.

1334
01:09:33,903 --> 01:09:36,167
We've just done a series
of tests and we'll do more.

1335
01:09:36,238 --> 01:09:38,729
It's just that right now, we're
really shooting in the dark.

1336
01:09:38,807 --> 01:09:40,866
We really appreciate
your honesty, Doctor.

1337
01:09:40,943 --> 01:09:42,843
It's strange. You know,
the LP we did

1338
01:09:42,912 --> 01:09:45,881
showed up an elevated protein
in the spinal fluid,

1339
01:09:45,948 --> 01:09:48,473
but the CAT scan showed
no evidence of

1340
01:09:48,551 --> 01:09:49,813
a stroke or tumor.

1341
01:09:49,885 --> 01:09:51,216
Those tests
should have been done

1342
01:09:51,287 --> 01:09:52,879
a long time ago,
shouldn't they?

1343
01:09:53,289 --> 01:09:54,722
We'll keep him in ICU,

1344
01:09:54,790 --> 01:09:56,587
that way he'll be
monitored at all times.

1345
01:09:56,659 --> 01:09:59,287
And I'll check in
and see him twice a day.

1346
01:09:59,929 --> 01:10:02,557
I'm going to move in here
with him, then, if it's okay.

1347
01:10:02,631 --> 01:10:04,895
I'm afraid, that's entirely
against hospital regulations.

1348
01:10:04,967 --> 01:10:07,197
Well, if it makes you
feel more comfortable,

1349
01:10:07,269 --> 01:10:08,827
I think
it's a good idea.

1350
01:12:22,338 --> 01:12:25,171
How long do you think
you can keep this up?

1351
01:12:25,974 --> 01:12:27,066
I don't know.

1352
01:12:27,142 --> 01:12:29,474
I'm just goin'
one day at a time.

1353
01:12:30,946 --> 01:12:32,277
I sit.

1354
01:12:33,215 --> 01:12:34,705
I talk to him.

1355
01:12:35,217 --> 01:12:38,311
I talk to myself.
I talk to people passing by.

1356
01:12:38,921 --> 01:12:41,685
I have this idea
if I'm sitting there

1357
01:12:41,890 --> 01:12:44,120
and I'm talking,
he won't die.

1358
01:12:45,194 --> 01:12:47,719
What are you going
to do when he does?

1359
01:12:48,997 --> 01:12:50,089
Annie, I don't-

1360
01:12:50,165 --> 01:12:53,134
You're the only one
who hasn't accepted it, John.

1361
01:12:55,871 --> 01:12:57,862
Why can't you let him go?

1362
01:12:58,040 --> 01:12:59,803
I can't explain it.

1363
01:13:01,443 --> 01:13:04,241
Maybe I want to be there
to mark the end.

1364
01:13:05,447 --> 01:13:06,937
I don't know.

1365
01:13:08,083 --> 01:13:09,573
To prove he was here.

1366
01:13:09,718 --> 01:13:11,242
To prove I was his son.

1367
01:13:11,954 --> 01:13:14,286
What more could you
possibly have done?

1368
01:13:14,356 --> 01:13:17,655
Annie, that man got up
every day of his life

1369
01:13:18,060 --> 01:13:19,789
and went to
a job he didn't like.

1370
01:13:19,928 --> 01:13:21,691
We didn't ask him to.

1371
01:13:22,598 --> 01:13:24,691
He just did it
because he was the father

1372
01:13:24,767 --> 01:13:26,598
and that was
the deal he made.

1373
01:13:26,668 --> 01:13:30,468
He didn't ask himself
if he was satisfied or happy.

1374
01:13:31,006 --> 01:13:33,531
He didn't even
know he had the right.

1375
01:13:33,842 --> 01:13:36,242
Somehow part of
that deal was that

1376
01:13:36,645 --> 01:13:38,510
we'd care for him
and watch over him

1377
01:13:38,614 --> 01:13:40,275
when he got older.

1378
01:13:42,284 --> 01:13:43,945
I screwed that up.

1379
01:13:44,319 --> 01:13:45,308
John.

1380
01:13:45,521 --> 01:13:47,614
I got embarrassed by him,

1381
01:13:48,390 --> 01:13:50,654
by the way Mom dominated him.

1382
01:13:51,627 --> 01:13:53,527
By the way he got old.

1383
01:13:54,897 --> 01:13:58,333
Embarrassed that
I had a marriage that failed,

1384
01:13:59,501 --> 01:14:01,628
a job that didn't make sense,

1385
01:14:01,703 --> 01:14:03,694
a son I'd barely recognize

1386
01:14:03,772 --> 01:14:05,672
if I passed him
on the street.

1387
01:14:06,241 --> 01:14:09,039
Maybe this is more
for me than for him,

1388
01:14:12,147 --> 01:14:14,707
but I'm gonna be there
when he dies.

1389
01:14:16,018 --> 01:14:18,043
And I'm gonna kiss him,

1390
01:14:19,721 --> 01:14:21,746
and I'm going to cover him,

1391
01:14:23,325 --> 01:14:25,555
and I'm gonna
mark the moment.

1392
01:14:29,097 --> 01:14:30,655
I owe him that.

1393
01:14:53,755 --> 01:14:56,019
When did you
get back in town?

1394
01:14:56,992 --> 01:14:59,517
I never left.
I'm staying with some friends.

1395
01:14:59,595 --> 01:15:01,688
I didn't want
to leave Grandpa.

1396
01:15:01,830 --> 01:15:04,298
You've been
coming here every day?

1397
01:15:04,933 --> 01:15:07,333
Whenever you leave,
one of the nurses calls me.

1398
01:15:07,402 --> 01:15:10,064
I usually stay
a half-an-hour or so.

1399
01:15:10,772 --> 01:15:13,138
I guess I dozed off. Sorry.

1400
01:16:03,325 --> 01:16:05,122
Where am I, Johnny?

1401
01:16:06,128 --> 01:16:07,755
You're in a hospital,
Dad.

1402
01:16:07,829 --> 01:16:10,161
I think I could
have guessed that one.

1403
01:16:10,232 --> 01:16:11,961
Why are you here?

1404
01:16:12,034 --> 01:16:14,764
Was there an earthquake
or a car crash or something?

1405
01:16:15,804 --> 01:16:16,896
He speaks?

1406
01:16:16,972 --> 01:16:18,405
Yes, he does.

1407
01:16:18,473 --> 01:16:20,464
It's something he
learned as a child.

1408
01:16:20,542 --> 01:16:23,033
Go, uh, go page Dr. Chad
right away.

1409
01:16:23,111 --> 01:16:24,840
Please, please.

1410
01:16:25,480 --> 01:16:27,414
Why was she
looking at me funny?

1411
01:16:27,482 --> 01:16:29,507
Uh, she's-she's part of
the hospital, Dad.

1412
01:16:29,585 --> 01:16:31,177
She's, uh, a nurse.

1413
01:16:31,253 --> 01:16:33,346
She's, uh... As a matter of
fact, these are all nurses.

1414
01:16:33,422 --> 01:16:36,653
This is Molly, this is
J.J., uh, this is Annie.

1415
01:16:37,526 --> 01:16:39,050
This is my dad.

1416
01:16:56,411 --> 01:16:57,776
Well, Mr. Tremont.

1417
01:16:57,846 --> 01:16:59,677
What can we do to
make you comfortable?

1418
01:16:59,748 --> 01:17:03,741
Well, to start with, you could
take out these pipes and wires.

1419
01:17:03,919 --> 01:17:06,217
Then maybe I could
have something to eat.

1420
01:17:06,288 --> 01:17:08,518
I feel like you've
been starving me here.

1421
01:17:08,590 --> 01:17:11,525
Okay, but we'll have to
start you off very slowly.

1422
01:17:11,593 --> 01:17:13,686
Don't forget you really
haven't eaten anything

1423
01:17:13,762 --> 01:17:15,627
in quite a long time.

1424
01:17:15,831 --> 01:17:17,594
Maybe that was what
was wrong with me.

1425
01:17:17,666 --> 01:17:19,361
Have you
thought of that?

1426
01:17:23,839 --> 01:17:26,672
All the tests are positive,
the vital signs stable.

1427
01:17:26,742 --> 01:17:28,403
This is the profile
of a healthy man.

1428
01:17:28,477 --> 01:17:29,842
What happened?
What's goin' on?

1429
01:17:29,911 --> 01:17:32,607
I've seen people recover
from comas before.

1430
01:17:32,681 --> 01:17:35,275
Very often we
never find out why.

1431
01:17:36,051 --> 01:17:38,747
I have some theories
in this case.

1432
01:17:38,920 --> 01:17:41,787
Nothing that I'd
want to see published.

1433
01:17:41,857 --> 01:17:43,222
Like what?

1434
01:17:43,925 --> 01:17:45,517
It is entirely possible

1435
01:17:45,594 --> 01:17:47,255
that he was so fearful
of the cancer

1436
01:17:47,329 --> 01:17:48,921
that his brain froze up,

1437
01:17:48,997 --> 01:17:50,828
stopped producing
a vital chemical

1438
01:17:50,899 --> 01:17:52,764
or enzyme that he needed.

1439
01:17:52,834 --> 01:17:55,894
Somehow with that last
variation of the IV mixture

1440
01:17:55,971 --> 01:17:58,804
we got lucky
and he replaced that enzyme.

1441
01:17:59,241 --> 01:18:00,401
I see.

1442
01:18:02,144 --> 01:18:04,112
You know,
if we were back home,

1443
01:18:04,179 --> 01:18:05,840
we'd say that it was
not that at all.

1444
01:18:05,914 --> 01:18:08,849
But rather,
it was your love and caring

1445
01:18:08,917 --> 01:18:12,114
that called your father back
from where he'd gone.

1446
01:18:12,521 --> 01:18:14,489
I think that I like
that one better.

1447
01:18:14,556 --> 01:18:15,818
Me, too.

1448
01:18:17,392 --> 01:18:18,916
Here they are.

1449
01:19:21,323 --> 01:19:22,585
What's goin' on, Dad?

1450
01:19:22,657 --> 01:19:23,885
What are you looking for?

1451
01:19:23,959 --> 01:19:25,256
Your mother and I

1452
01:19:25,360 --> 01:19:27,089
are starting
a new life together, Johnny.

1453
01:19:27,162 --> 01:19:29,187
We need
some new clothes.

1454
01:19:31,399 --> 01:19:33,890
Hey, nice day. How you doing?

1455
01:19:34,536 --> 01:19:36,128
I don't know, Dad.

1456
01:19:36,204 --> 01:19:38,900
What do you suppose
Mom will say about all this?

1457
01:19:38,974 --> 01:19:42,671
She'll probably laugh and call
me crazy, but she'll laugh.

1458
01:19:43,378 --> 01:19:45,312
We haven't had
enough laughter in our house

1459
01:19:45,380 --> 01:19:47,245
for the past 10 years.

1460
01:19:53,188 --> 01:19:54,917
What do you think of that?

1461
01:19:56,625 --> 01:19:58,149
Thank you.
Thank you, thank you.

1462
01:19:58,226 --> 01:20:00,751
Ladies, ladies,
the show is about to begin.

1463
01:20:00,829 --> 01:20:02,319
No matter how
stimulated you become

1464
01:20:02,397 --> 01:20:03,625
during the performance,

1465
01:20:03,698 --> 01:20:06,166
please remain in your seats
at all times.

1466
01:20:08,403 --> 01:20:12,499
The house is proud to present
the star of our show,

1467
01:20:12,574 --> 01:20:15,975
the late sick man
and almost corpus delicti,

1468
01:20:16,044 --> 01:20:19,013
back from a successful tour
of the Caribbean,

1469
01:20:19,314 --> 01:20:21,043
Gorgeous Jake.

1470
01:20:21,149 --> 01:20:22,480
Give him a big hand.

1471
01:20:22,584 --> 01:20:24,484
Come on, give him a big hand.

1472
01:20:25,987 --> 01:20:26,976
Here we go.

1473
01:20:27,055 --> 01:20:30,684
Also his faithful companion,
Billy!

1474
01:20:30,759 --> 01:20:32,852
Ladies and gentlemen, Billy!

1475
01:20:33,195 --> 01:20:35,425
What is this? What's it for?

1476
01:20:35,497 --> 01:20:39,228
This is my outfit
for bicycling in Venice

1477
01:20:39,301 --> 01:20:40,734
down on the beach.

1478
01:20:40,802 --> 01:20:42,770
And maybe roller skating.

1479
01:20:42,838 --> 01:20:46,001
And this? This is my
baseball-watching outfit.

1480
01:20:46,074 --> 01:20:47,200
See?

1481
01:20:47,275 --> 01:20:49,505
I think I'll wear it mostly
only in the house.

1482
01:20:49,578 --> 01:20:51,705
Actually, I'm going
to go see a few of the games,

1483
01:20:51,780 --> 01:20:52,974
but not in my outfit.

1484
01:20:53,048 --> 01:20:54,777
That's good to hear, Jake.

1485
01:20:55,217 --> 01:20:56,946
Wait. There's more.

1486
01:21:13,001 --> 01:21:14,901
Let me see that again.

1487
01:21:27,315 --> 01:21:29,112
Oh, I'll piss
my pants!

1488
01:21:34,456 --> 01:21:37,983
Tell them to stop.
I'm dying!

1489
01:21:38,293 --> 01:21:42,024
I never heard of anybody
dying from laughing, Bette.

1490
01:21:42,931 --> 01:21:44,956
But wouldn't that be nice?

1491
01:21:53,541 --> 01:21:56,203
I tell you, Johnny,
he's not the same.

1492
01:21:56,344 --> 01:21:59,643
Maybe his hormones got
mixed up with someone else's.

1493
01:21:59,848 --> 01:22:02,681
You know what goes
on in these hospitals.

1494
01:22:07,322 --> 01:22:09,688
Nobody would
believe he's a 78-year-old man

1495
01:22:09,758 --> 01:22:11,316
who almost
died a few weeks ago.

1496
01:22:11,393 --> 01:22:13,623
You've got to talk with
somebody, I'm serious.

1497
01:22:13,695 --> 01:22:15,754
Mom,
he's just having fun.

1498
01:22:17,699 --> 01:22:20,259
Not bad.
I shot a 94.

1499
01:22:20,936 --> 01:22:23,496
It's a one-hole course,
but still...

1500
01:22:23,571 --> 01:22:25,368
It's a wonderful day.

1501
01:22:25,440 --> 01:22:27,635
How about I take us
for a drive after breakfast?

1502
01:22:27,709 --> 01:22:29,006
Ah, it's
a good idea.

1503
01:22:29,077 --> 01:22:30,544
Maybe Mom will
come along with us.

1504
01:22:30,612 --> 01:22:32,307
I'm not going to
drive with him.

1505
01:22:32,380 --> 01:22:34,211
He drove too fast before.

1506
01:22:34,349 --> 01:22:36,214
I hate to think
what he'd be like now.

1507
01:22:36,284 --> 01:22:38,684
Don't you worry your
pretty little head, Bette.

1508
01:22:38,753 --> 01:22:41,119
With old Jake Tremont
behind that wheel,

1509
01:22:41,189 --> 01:22:43,817
you're as safe as if
you were in your own bed.

1510
01:22:43,892 --> 01:22:45,985
And it's almost as much fun.

1511
01:23:00,275 --> 01:23:02,243
What on Earth are
you looking for?

1512
01:23:02,310 --> 01:23:05,677
Nothing. I want to see
if I can still do a pushup.

1513
01:23:17,859 --> 01:23:20,419
I'll call these
"old man pushups. "

1514
01:23:25,166 --> 01:23:26,997
What about it, Bette?

1515
01:23:27,202 --> 01:23:29,227
You want to hit the beach?

1516
01:23:29,704 --> 01:23:32,502
I'll go,
but only in a taxicab.

1517
01:23:36,244 --> 01:23:38,371
I don't want to go in a cab.

1518
01:23:40,982 --> 01:23:43,610
We'd probably wind
up in Santa Monica.

1519
01:23:44,419 --> 01:23:48,048
That town is
an outside old people's home.

1520
01:23:48,390 --> 01:23:51,553
On every corner,
a doctor's office or a bank.

1521
01:23:51,993 --> 01:23:53,858
I'd like to drive to Venice.

1522
01:23:53,928 --> 01:23:56,089
Maybe to the pier.
Get in a little fishin'.

1523
01:23:56,798 --> 01:23:59,096
Oh, I used to like fishin'.

1524
01:24:02,504 --> 01:24:04,529
Where's all my fishing gear?

1525
01:24:04,606 --> 01:24:07,131
I think I put it away
in the garage.

1526
01:24:09,944 --> 01:24:11,707
About 35 years ago.

1527
01:24:11,913 --> 01:24:13,312
I'll get it.

1528
01:24:17,485 --> 01:24:19,453
Well, whatever's
going on with Dad,

1529
01:24:19,521 --> 01:24:20,988
I think
it's pretty terrific.

1530
01:24:22,490 --> 01:24:24,788
Oh, come on.
It's going to be okay.

1531
01:24:25,393 --> 01:24:27,122
Johnny, I'm scared.

1532
01:24:27,462 --> 01:24:29,930
He's talking about
people I don't even know,

1533
01:24:29,998 --> 01:24:32,159
or people
I'm sure are dead.

1534
01:24:32,233 --> 01:24:35,760
He says we live on a farm
in Cape May, New Jersey

1535
01:24:35,837 --> 01:24:37,668
and he wants us
all to go back there

1536
01:24:37,739 --> 01:24:39,764
because it's
harvest time.

1537
01:24:40,475 --> 01:24:41,601
What?

1538
01:24:56,991 --> 01:24:58,083
