01:37:22,036 --> 01:37:24,004
This other life, Jake,

1789
01:37:26,073 --> 01:37:27,370
it hurts.

1790
01:37:29,276 --> 01:37:31,608
Was it so terrible here
with me?

1791
01:37:32,813 --> 01:37:35,304
We just got off
the track a little.

1792
01:37:36,584 --> 01:37:37,778
A lot.

1793
01:37:39,453 --> 01:37:41,478
You're asking me
to turn my back

1794
01:37:41,555 --> 01:37:43,045
on our whole life together?

1795
01:37:43,757 --> 01:37:44,985
Oh, no.

1796
01:37:46,393 --> 01:37:48,418
I'm asking you to
remember the life

1797
01:37:48,495 --> 01:37:50,224
that we wanted to have.

1798
01:37:50,664 --> 01:37:53,394
God, Bette. You took
it all on by yourself,

1799
01:37:53,467 --> 01:37:54,957
didn't you?
And I let you.

1800
01:37:57,504 --> 01:37:59,199
You were so good.

1801
01:38:00,140 --> 01:38:03,337
I'm asking you to
let go a little. Open up.

1802
01:38:04,144 --> 01:38:06,874
Not just to me,
but to the world.

1803
01:38:07,615 --> 01:38:10,607
We used to have
such good times, remember?

1804
01:38:10,684 --> 01:38:12,709
We used to dance together

1805
01:38:13,020 --> 01:38:14,578
all slow.

1806
01:38:14,722 --> 01:38:17,486
You were such
a wonderful dancer.

1807
01:38:20,160 --> 01:38:23,561
And I want to dance with you
again before I die.

1808
01:38:24,265 --> 01:38:26,233
Don't talk
about dying.

1809
01:38:26,433 --> 01:38:29,061
That's okay.
We're all going to die.

1810
01:38:29,570 --> 01:38:31,333
Dying is not a sin.

1811
01:38:33,140 --> 01:38:34,664
Not living is.

1812
01:40:06,000 --> 01:40:07,262
Good morning, Mother.

1813
01:40:07,334 --> 01:40:08,562
Good morning.

1814
01:40:22,683 --> 01:40:24,048
Nice outfit.

1815
01:40:24,184 --> 01:40:25,549
Your father likes it.

1816
01:40:34,962 --> 01:40:36,429
Mr. Tremont?

1817
01:40:37,765 --> 01:40:39,392
I have some news.

1818
01:40:40,667 --> 01:40:42,191
It's not good.

1819
01:40:43,003 --> 01:40:44,368
What is it?

1820
01:40:45,606 --> 01:40:48,734
Well, of course it's not
the same in all cases,

1821
01:40:48,909 --> 01:40:50,536
but it seems, uh...

1822
01:40:52,079 --> 01:40:55,276
It's okay, good doctor,
you can tell me the truth.

1823
01:40:58,018 --> 01:40:59,610
Cancer's back.

1824
01:41:02,756 --> 01:41:04,223
It's spread.

1825
01:41:04,925 --> 01:41:06,916
It's in the lymph system.

1826
01:41:10,230 --> 01:41:11,561
How long?

1827
01:41:12,132 --> 01:41:13,497
It's difficult to say.

1828
01:41:13,567 --> 01:41:15,194
Different patients
respond differently.

1829
01:41:15,602 --> 01:41:16,864
Dr. Chad?

1830
01:41:20,140 --> 01:41:21,607
I don't know.

1831
01:41:38,125 --> 01:41:40,184
Hey, Dad, what are
you doing up so late?

1832
01:41:40,260 --> 01:41:41,591
Waiting for you.

1833
01:41:42,396 --> 01:41:43,727
Why?

1834
01:41:44,064 --> 01:41:45,929
You realize your
mother and I separated

1835
01:41:45,999 --> 01:41:48,524
before you were old enough
to stay out late?

1836
01:41:49,636 --> 01:41:51,001
I think I feel

1837
01:41:52,139 --> 01:41:55,939
deprived of my divine right
as a father to worry.

1838
01:41:56,143 --> 01:41:58,338
Do you want me go out
and come back in again?

1839
01:41:58,412 --> 01:42:01,142
No, I want you to sit
down and talk to me.

1840
01:42:04,585 --> 01:42:07,019
What would you
like to talk about?

1841
01:42:08,288 --> 01:42:11,052
I'm trying to think of
something I can tell you.

1842
01:42:11,125 --> 01:42:13,923
Some fatherly advice
you can take back with you.

1843
01:42:13,994 --> 01:42:15,461
Some insight.

1844
01:42:16,263 --> 01:42:18,356
I can't think of anything.

1845
01:42:19,299 --> 01:42:21,631
I think it's me.
I think it's...

1846
01:42:22,669 --> 01:42:25,866
I think it's tough for guys
my age to reach out.

1847
01:42:29,877 --> 01:42:31,742
You know,
every time we see each other,

1848
01:42:31,812 --> 01:42:33,245
it's always on the fly.

1849
01:42:33,313 --> 01:42:35,076
You're going or I'm coming,

1850
01:42:35,149 --> 01:42:37,174
or we're at
somebody's wedding.

1851
01:42:37,651 --> 01:42:40,950
We're always talking
over suitcases and backpacks

1852
01:42:41,421 --> 01:42:43,889
or holding little
sandwiches in our hand.

1853
01:42:46,827 --> 01:42:49,125
I don't know a lot
about you.

1854
01:42:49,229 --> 01:42:50,662
Well, um,

1855
01:42:52,166 --> 01:42:53,895
let's see, I'm 5' 11",

1856
01:42:53,967 --> 01:42:56,162
I like sports,
I'm into bikes-

1857
01:42:56,236 --> 01:42:58,704
Don't do that.
Don't-don't make a joke.

1858
01:43:00,207 --> 01:43:02,732
You know, we always do that.
We come close

1859
01:43:02,910 --> 01:43:04,343
to-to saying something real

1860
01:43:04,411 --> 01:43:06,003
and then one of us
makes a joke.

1861
01:43:06,813 --> 01:43:08,212
Talk to me.

1862
01:43:09,383 --> 01:43:11,214
Tell me about Mexico.

1863
01:43:12,486 --> 01:43:14,147
I like it there.

1864
01:43:14,855 --> 01:43:17,289
It's not like school.
There's no pressure.

1865
01:43:17,357 --> 01:43:20,292
Uh, the people are
real and thoughtful.

1866
01:43:21,228 --> 01:43:22,217
Um,

1867
01:43:23,263 --> 01:43:26,198
the days have kind of
a nice rhythm to 'em.

1868
01:43:26,800 --> 01:43:28,927
You have a lot
of friends there?

1869
01:43:29,002 --> 01:43:30,993
Yeah, there's
about five of us.

1870
01:43:31,071 --> 01:43:32,868
You know,
we live as a group.

1871
01:43:33,607 --> 01:43:34,835
We take turns workin'.

1872
01:43:34,908 --> 01:43:36,068
We share everything we make.

1873
01:43:36,143 --> 01:43:38,771
We share the cleaning,
the housework.

1874
01:43:38,979 --> 01:43:40,708
It's a real family.

1875
01:43:42,616 --> 01:43:44,846
The other guys
from your school, too?

1876
01:43:44,918 --> 01:43:47,011
Well, two of the guys
are girls.

1877
01:43:51,291 --> 01:43:53,316
The world has changed, Billy.

1878
01:43:53,393 --> 01:43:54,724
You can't believe

1879
01:43:54,795 --> 01:43:56,160
the way
the world has changed.

1880
01:43:57,898 --> 01:44:00,059
Why was making money
always more important to you

1881
01:44:00,133 --> 01:44:01,691
than me or Mom?

1882
01:44:01,935 --> 01:44:02,924
Oh.

1883
01:44:03,136 --> 01:44:04,433
You said you wanted to talk.

1884
01:44:04,571 --> 01:44:05,868
All right.

1885
01:44:10,043 --> 01:44:12,807
Because, uh, that's what
I thought a man was.

1886
01:44:13,614 --> 01:44:17,243
What I thought a father was.
Some guy who wore a suit

1887
01:44:17,551 --> 01:44:19,519
and made a lot of money.

1888
01:44:23,590 --> 01:44:25,683
All right, that's too easy.

1889
01:44:27,394 --> 01:44:29,760
Because I liked
the power of it.

1890
01:44:30,430 --> 01:44:32,830
I liked being the guy
who got the job done,

1891
01:44:32,899 --> 01:44:35,163
the guy who
everybody comes to.

1892
01:44:35,369 --> 01:44:38,031
And something had to give

1893
01:44:39,706 --> 01:44:41,503
and it was my family.

1894
01:44:41,775 --> 01:44:43,902
Well, I would never do that.

1895
01:44:44,711 --> 01:44:46,872
I would never run away
from my family.

1896
01:44:46,947 --> 01:44:49,848
Leaving was
the toughest thing I ever did.

1897
01:44:51,485 --> 01:44:52,816
It didn't seem like it.

1898
01:44:52,886 --> 01:44:53,910
Well, that's because

1899
01:44:53,987 --> 01:44:55,978
we tried to make it
look normal.

1900
01:44:56,590 --> 01:44:58,854
That's what all
the books said to do.

1901
01:44:58,925 --> 01:45:00,756
The "normal" divorce.

1902
01:45:02,062 --> 01:45:03,825
But there was pain.

1903
01:45:03,897 --> 01:45:06,297
A lot. There still is.

1904
01:45:09,569 --> 01:45:11,469
I've missed you, Billy.

1905
01:45:11,805 --> 01:45:15,764
And you may not need me
or even want me around.

1906
01:45:16,977 --> 01:45:19,411
But I'd like to stay
in your life.

1907
01:45:20,914 --> 01:45:22,506
I'm your father.

1908
01:45:30,157 --> 01:45:33,149
I guess there is some advice
I'd like to give you.

1909
01:45:33,226 --> 01:45:34,386
To give to a guy

1910
01:45:34,461 --> 01:45:35,826
who's about to
take on the world.

1911
01:45:36,730 --> 01:45:38,095
What is it?

1912
01:45:40,434 --> 01:45:41,924
Be forgiving.

1913
01:45:57,250 --> 01:46:00,083
Hi.
How's he doing?

1914
01:46:00,721 --> 01:46:03,281
Okay.
He slept a little.

1915
01:46:03,357 --> 01:46:05,120
You've been
here all afternoon?

1916
01:46:05,192 --> 01:46:07,387
He does better
when I'm here.

1917
01:46:07,994 --> 01:46:10,360
Come on, let's go down
and get something to eat.

1918
01:46:10,430 --> 01:46:11,829
The doctor
will be here soon.

1919
01:46:11,898 --> 01:46:13,263
I don't want to
miss him.

1920
01:46:13,333 --> 01:46:15,028
Go ahead.
I'll come get you.

1921
01:46:15,102 --> 01:46:16,399
Come on.

1922
01:46:41,161 --> 01:46:42,719
Where's Mother?

1923
01:46:43,063 --> 01:46:45,588
She went down with Billy
to get something to eat.

1924
01:46:45,665 --> 01:46:46,996
Oh, good.

1925
01:46:48,935 --> 01:46:50,493
How you feelin'?

1926
01:46:52,205 --> 01:46:53,263
Perfect.

1927
01:46:53,340 --> 01:46:54,307
Yeah, I can tell.

1928
01:46:54,941 --> 01:46:56,602
You know what I've
been thinking about?

1929
01:46:56,676 --> 01:46:58,007
What?

1930
01:46:58,078 --> 01:47:00,876
1947 World Series.

1931
01:47:01,181 --> 01:47:02,148
What?

1932
01:47:02,215 --> 01:47:03,944
Isn't that crazy?
I know, I mean,

1933
01:47:05,085 --> 01:47:06,552
at a time like this,

1934
01:47:06,653 --> 01:47:08,621
I should be having
very deep thoughts.

1935
01:47:09,756 --> 01:47:10,984
I'm trying,

1936
01:47:11,091 --> 01:47:13,389
but all that keeps going
through my mind is

1937
01:47:13,460 --> 01:47:16,452
old ball games
and old TV themes.

1938
01:47:22,202 --> 01:47:23,464
Bonanza.

1939
01:47:23,804 --> 01:47:25,271
Oh, this is great,
Dad.

1940
01:47:25,338 --> 01:47:27,329
What about
the '47 World Series?

1941
01:47:27,407 --> 01:47:28,965
How's that fit in?

1942
01:47:29,976 --> 01:47:31,944
It produced one of
the great moments

1943
01:47:32,012 --> 01:47:33,707
in baseball history.

1944
01:47:34,514 --> 01:47:36,072
They were between

1945
01:47:36,149 --> 01:47:38,617
the Yankee centerfielder
Joe DiMaggio,

1946
01:47:39,319 --> 01:47:42,117
the Prince of Players,
the Star of Stars,

1947
01:47:43,089 --> 01:47:45,353
and the Dodger left-fielder,

1948
01:47:45,425 --> 01:47:49,327
Al Gionfriddo,
a second-stringer.

1949
01:47:49,896 --> 01:47:52,660
He only played that day because
the regular left-fielder,

1950
01:47:52,732 --> 01:47:54,893
Carl Furillo, got hurt.

1951
01:47:55,869 --> 01:47:57,769
Do you know this story?

1952
01:47:58,071 --> 01:47:59,595
Tell it to me.

1953
01:48:01,141 --> 01:48:02,904
Well, in the sixth game,

1954
01:48:03,677 --> 01:48:07,340
bottom of the sixth inning,
it was 8-5, Dodgers.

1955
01:48:08,415 --> 01:48:10,280
Two on, two out.

1956
01:48:11,418 --> 01:48:13,409
Up steps DiMaggio.

1957
01:48:14,221 --> 01:48:17,088
Hit a smash,
deep left field,

1958
01:48:17,157 --> 01:48:19,591
had home run
written all over it.

1959
01:48:19,659 --> 01:48:21,422
Everyone in
the stands knew it.

1960
01:48:21,495 --> 01:48:25,295
I knew it. DiMaggio knew it.
It was perfect.

1961
01:48:25,999 --> 01:48:30,299
But here comes this
little Gionfriddo guy.

1962
01:48:30,504 --> 01:48:32,404
He's racing
after the ball.

1963
01:48:32,472 --> 01:48:35,669
And he doesn't realize
it was hit by Joe DiMaggio.

1964
01:48:36,943 --> 01:48:40,936
At the last possible moment,
he jumps.

1965
01:48:41,781 --> 01:48:43,942
Reaches over the rail,

1966
01:48:46,052 --> 01:48:49,818
robs DiMaggio
of a three-run homer. Hmm.

1967
01:48:50,457 --> 01:48:53,551
It was an incredible catch.
It'll live forever.

1968
01:48:53,894 --> 01:48:55,054
But

1969
01:48:55,795 --> 01:48:58,662
then comes
the really amazing thing.

1970
01:49:00,667 --> 01:49:03,659
DiMaggio was just approaching
second base

1971
01:49:03,737 --> 01:49:07,901
when he sees Gionfriddo
make this catch.

1972
01:49:08,909 --> 01:49:12,777
He got so upset,
he kicked the dirt.

1973
01:49:16,316 --> 01:49:18,113
How do you like that?

1974
01:49:20,353 --> 01:49:24,255
This man who never
showed any emotion,

1975
01:49:26,192 --> 01:49:28,092
he was human after all.

1976
01:49:29,329 --> 01:49:33,060
And it took Al Gionfriddo
to bring it out.

1977
01:49:35,669 --> 01:49:37,967
You know what
that means to me?

1978
01:49:38,438 --> 01:49:39,700
What?

1979
01:49:40,407 --> 01:49:43,774
In America,
anything is possible

1980
01:49:44,210 --> 01:49:46,201
if you show up for work.

1981
01:49:54,588 --> 01:49:56,852
Sometimes I wish
I'd held you more

1982
01:49:56,957 --> 01:49:58,288
when you were a kid.

1983
01:50:00,293 --> 01:50:02,227
I wish I kissed you more.

1984
01:50:02,295 --> 01:50:04,490
You did fine, Dad,
just fine.

1985
01:50:06,666 --> 01:50:09,032
Do you know
how much I love you?

1986
01:50:10,904 --> 01:50:11,893
Yeah.

1987
01:50:34,094 --> 01:50:36,187
A lot has happened,
Johnny.

1988
01:50:37,230 --> 01:50:39,061
Some good, some bad.

1989
01:50:42,602 --> 01:50:45,036
But when I look
at you, I know,

1990
01:50:47,107 --> 01:50:49,507
I must have done
something right.

1991
01:51:05,892 --> 01:51:07,519
Honey, I'm gonna
put these in the car.

1992
01:51:07,594 --> 01:51:08,822
Okay.

1993
01:51:08,895 --> 01:51:09,987
Did you
talk to Mom?

1994
01:51:10,063 --> 01:51:11,587
Yeah. Mom will stay
here for now.

1995
01:51:11,665 --> 01:51:13,292
At least till the middle of next month.

1996
01:51:13,366 --> 01:51:14,355
And then we'll see.

1997
01:51:14,434 --> 01:51:15,423
All right.

1998
01:51:15,502 --> 01:51:17,402
I think she'll be okay.

1999
01:51:24,544 --> 01:51:26,444
How you holding up?

2000
01:51:27,013 --> 01:51:28,412
I miss him.

2001
01:51:29,082 --> 01:51:30,344
Yeah, me too.

2002
01:51:32,352 --> 01:51:34,786
Go ahead,
I'll catch up with you.

2003
01:51:37,590 --> 01:51:39,217
I need a minute.

2004
01:52:05,518 --> 01:52:06,815
Go ahead.

2005
01:52:07,287 --> 01:52:08,276
Um...

2006
01:52:10,990 --> 01:52:12,355
Grandpa,

2007
01:52:12,959 --> 01:52:14,426
we just wanted
to take some time

2008
01:52:14,494 --> 01:52:16,359
to say good-bye our way.

2009
01:52:16,429 --> 01:52:18,363
I- I guess
it's your way.

2010
01:52:18,965 --> 01:52:19,954
Um,

2011
01:52:20,066 --> 01:52:22,125
and this seemed like
the right place to do it.

2012
01:52:22,202 --> 01:52:23,965
Because there's so much
of you in here.

2013
01:52:24,037 --> 01:52:26,437
So much that's
alive and growing.

2014
01:52:27,273 --> 01:52:29,707
Which is still
how I think of you.

2015
01:52:30,343 --> 01:52:31,605
It's going to be funny.

2016
01:52:31,678 --> 01:52:32,702
Yeah.

2017
01:52:36,850 --> 01:52:39,785
Grandpa, I love you
and I miss you already.

2018
01:52:43,823 --> 01:52:46,485
Dad and I are here
and we're together.

2019
01:52:49,729 --> 01:52:52,823
This is good.
This is a good idea.

2020
01:52:54,334 --> 01:52:55,824
I feel better.

2021
01:52:57,637 --> 01:52:58,968
Me, too.

